For example: {{.../secure/application}} should take you to the "Search Applications" screen, as should {{.../secure/application/view}}

The {{.action}} should not be necessary.

Directory browsing should not be allowed - try going to {{.../secure/application}} to see what I mean.

There seems to be a problem with the CrowdProvider not passing along enough information to create a user in OpenDS, since JIRA creates the user with just the username first and provides all other attributes later.  It fails with the following error:
{noformat}
com.atlassian.crowd.integration.exception.InvalidPrincipalException: Operation failed; nested exception is javax.naming.directory.InvalidAttributeValueException: [LDAP: error code 21 - Entry "cn=duffy,ou=People,dc=atlassian,dc=com" contains a value "" for attribute sn that is invalid according to the syntax for that attribute:  The operation attempted to assign a zero-length value to an attribute with the directory string syntax]; remaining name 'cn=duffy,ou=People,dc=atlassian,dc=com'
{noformat}

Creating the user via Crowd works fine, as all the attributes are provided up-front.

I'm running into an issue when trying to remove a group in the Crowd admin console's View Group screen.

If you switch to the Principals tab (to see who is in the group before deleting it) the Remove Group link no longer works properly.  It appears the group name is being lost in the URL when you switch tabs.

When you first open the View Group screen, the Remove Group link points to:

{code}
/crowd/console/secure/group/removegroup.action?directoryID=123456&name=my-group
{code}

But if you switch to the Principals tab, the link is missing the group name: 

{code}
/crowd/console/secure/group/removegroup.action?directoryID=123456
{code}

When running from Tomcat installed via 'yum', the log files are rather indiscriminately sent to the current directory.  The filename should be prefixed with ${catalina.base}/logs such as:

{code}
log4j.appender.filelog.File=${catalina.base}/logs/atlassian-crowd-openid-client.log
{code}

There may be another way to do this, but I don't have time to look it all up :-)

Basically, Fedora and CentOS will bring up tomcat at boot, and inevitably, the current directory is not a good place to dump logs.  This fixes it.

Currently the logging will show the following:
{noformat}
17:00:00,015 ERROR atlassian.crowd.model.token.TokenDAOMemory: Failed to find Token with key com.atlassian.crowd.model.token.Token in cache.
{noformat}

This should actually be:
{noformat}
17:00:00,015 ERROR atlassian.crowd.model.token.TokenDAOMemory: Failed to find Token with '==HBDJSDKJq2323==' in cache.
{noformat}
